<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Central, Eastern [Kenya (!), Taita Hills, Ngangao (BAQ)] and Western Africa; Australian, Eastern Palaearctic, and Oriental regions (Fig. 336).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
This genus is probably polyphagous and has been reported mainly from the following plant families: 
<taxonomicName genus="Epacridaceae" lsidName="Epacridaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Epacridaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Urticaceae" lsidName="Urticaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Urticaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Cyatheaceae" lsidName="Cyatheaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Cyatheaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Asteraceae" lsidName="Asteraceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Arecaceae" lsidName="Arecaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Arecaceae</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="An essay about the relationships between the leaf-beetles and their food-plants. Backhuys Publishers, Leiden" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" title="Host-plants of Chrysomelidae of the World." year="1995">Jolivet and Hawkeswood 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
